<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOLDEN WEST WOMEN WIN BIG, GAIN BERTH IN STATE TOURNAMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE KRESAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
UNTINGTON BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
den West College gained its fourth consecutive berth in the state women's 
basketball tournament with a 130-80 victory over El Camino Saturday at Golden 
West. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West (34-1) will enter the tournament, which begins Thursday at College 
of the Sequoias in Visalia, as the top-seeded team from Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
The victory marked the school-record sixth consecutive time the Rustlers have 
scored more than 100 points in a game. It was also the school-record 13th time 
in a season that the Rustlers have scored more than 100 points. 
</P>
<P>
"Well, we made it again," Golden West Coach Dick Stricklin said. "We knew it 
was going to be a run-and-gun game because that's what they like to do as much 
as we do." 
</P>
<P>
Golden West had defeated Antelope Valley, 115-61, in the first round of the 
playoffs Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West led, 61-44, after a physical first half Saturday; the Rustlers' 
Shawna Armstrong had to leave the game in the first minute when she was hit in 
the stomach. 
</P>
<P>
Armstrong returned six minutes later and finished with a team-high 24 points. 
</P>
<P>
Her substitute, Micki Hamilton, scored a team-high 16 points in the first half 
and finished with 21. 
</P>
<P>
Donna Gondringer added 21 points and Claudette Jackson 16 for Golden West. 
</P>
<P>
Lynn Sherman had 37 points for El Camino (22-8). STEVE KRESAL 
</P>
</TEXT>
